Consider the following grammar (that admits a series of declarations, followed by expressions) and the associated syntax directed translation (SDT) actions, given as pseudo-code:

P -> DE
D -> D id : T  { if (D.type == T.type) D.type = T.type; else D.type = bool; }
E -> E + E_1   { check that E.type == E_1.type; set E.type = int; }
E -> E_1       { E.type = E_1.type; }
E -> ID(of type int)  { E.type = int; }

With respect to the above grammar, which one of the following choices is correct?

A. The actions can be used to correctly type-check any syntactically correct boolean variable declarations and boolean expressions.
B. The actions can be used to correctly type-check any syntactically correct integer variable declarations and integer expressions.
C. The actions can be used to type-check syntactically correct boolean variable declarations and boolean expressions, but not integer variable declarations and integer expressions.
D. The actions will lead to an infinite loop.

